Aids Drug

Sammy

May 22, 2020

Introduction

A new preventative aides (triUmpsal) is under test in clinical trials. Analyze the effectiveness of this drug across the board. Consider population subgroups by gender, drug use, and sexual orientation. Finish this!

Methods

Since each question is categorical-categorical we use the same methods in each.

Graphical summary: bar chart Numeric summary: cross tabulation, table form. Inference: Chi-squared test, and Fishers exact test.

The conclusions for all questions will be summarized in at the end.

does the vacine effect whether one contracts aids or not in the general population?

\(H_0\): The vacine has no effect that one contracts aids or not.

\(H_A\): The vacine does have an effect.

Results

Descriptive Results

Graphical Descriptive Results

barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=triUmp,type = "percent" )

The bar charts shows among those who got aids looks like fewer contracted aids if they had the vacine.

basicCC <- ggplot(triUmp,aes(x=infected,fill=treatment))
basicCC + geom_bar()

basicCC + geom_bar(position=position_dodge())

Numerical Descriptive Results

table1 <- xtabs(~infected + treatment,data=triUmp)
rowPerc(table1)
##         treatment
## infected   drug placebo  Total
##     aids  40.87   59.13 100.00
##     none  49.10   50.90 100.00
colPerc(table1)
##         treatment
## infected   drug placebo
##    aids    3.99    5.49
##    none   96.01   94.51
##    Total 100.00  100.00

these tables show the numerical results by percentage

Inferential Results

chisq.test(table1)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  table1
## X-squared = 26.41, df = 1, p-value = 2.761e-07
chisqtestGC(table1)
## Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction 
## 
## Observed Counts:
##         treatment
## infected  drug placebo
##     aids   423     612
##     none 10168   10540
## 
## Counts Expected by Null:
##         treatment
## infected     drug  placebo
##     aids   504.15   530.85
##     none 10086.85 10621.15
## 
## Contributions to the chi-square statistic:
##         treatment
## infected  drug placebo
##     aids 13.06   12.40
##     none  0.65    0.62
## 
## 
## Chi-Square Statistic = 26.4104 
## Degrees of Freedom of the table = 1 
## P-Value = 0
fisher.test(table1)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  table1
## p-value = 2.333e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6295438 0.8148378
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##  0.7164774

The chances are 2 in a billion that we would get these results if the NH were true. therefore we reject the NH.

question2

does the vacine effect whether one contracts aids or not among females.

\(H_0\): The vacine has no effect that one contracts aids or not.

\(H_A\): The vacine does have an effect.

Results

Descriptive Results

Graphical Descriptive Results

females <- filter(triUmp,gender =="F")
barchartGC(~infected + treatment,data=females,type = "percent" )

The bar charts shows that it did have an affect on weather female aquired aids. The affect show that it worked backwards. They received aids more.

The bar chart shows tht vacine did effect wheater a female contacted aids by making them more susceptible.

basicCC <- ggplot(females,aes(x=infected,fill=treatment))
basicCC + geom_bar()

basicCC + geom_bar(position=position_dodge())

Numerical Descriptive Results

table2 <- xtabs(~infected + treatment,data=females)
rowPerc(table2)
##         treatment
## infected   drug placebo  Total
##     aids  58.82   41.18 100.00
##     none  48.06   51.94 100.00
colPerc(table2)
##         treatment
## infected   drug placebo
##    aids    3.69    2.42
##    none   96.31   97.58
##    Total 100.00  100.00

these tables show blah blah blah

Inferential Results

chisq.test(table2)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  table2
## X-squared = 15.634, df = 1, p-value = 7.686e-05
chisqtestGC(table2)
## Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction 
## 
## Observed Counts:
##         treatment
## infected drug placebo
##     aids  210     147
##     none 5484    5927
## 
## Counts Expected by Null:
##         treatment
## infected    drug placebo
##     aids  172.74  184.26
##     none 5521.26 5889.74
## 
## Contributions to the chi-square statistic:
##         treatment
## infected drug placebo
##     aids 8.04    7.54
##     none 0.25    0.24
## 
## 
## Chi-Square Statistic = 15.6339 
## Degrees of Freedom of the table = 1 
## P-Value = 1e-04
fisher.test(table2)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  table2
## p-value = 6.596e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.240408 1.925729
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##   1.543902

The chances are 2 in a billion that we would get these results if the NH were true. there fore we reject the NH.

Discussion and Conclusion

Pvalue is less than .05, therefore we reject the NH. The vacine worked backwards so female population should avoid the vacine.
